<h2>Expert Tips</h2>
<ol class="list-decimal list-inside space-y-4 text-gray-700">
  <li><strong>Match Wine Weight to Salmon Preparation Method</strong> - Grilled or blackened salmon's char and smoke require full-bodied reds like Oregon Pinot Noir or Côte-Rôtie Syrah, while poached or steamed salmon pairs beautifully with lighter whites like Sancerre or Grüner Veltliner. The protein's natural oils need wine with sufficient acidity to cleanse the palate—aim for wines with at least 6-7 grams per liter of total acidity.</li>

  <li><strong>Temperature Precision Enhances the Pairing</strong> - Serve white wines at 45-50°F to highlight their mineral backbone against salmon's richness, while light reds should be chilled to 55-58°F to prevent overpowering the fish's delicate texture. Warmer temperatures can make the wine taste flabby against salmon's natural oils, disrupting the balance.</li>

  <li><strong>Consider Salmon Species for Wine Selection</strong> - Atlantic salmon's higher fat content pairs excellently with Champagne or Crémant whose bubbles cut through the richness, while leaner Pacific varieties like Coho work beautifully with crisp Albariño or Muscadet. King salmon's buttery texture demands wines with more structure—think aged Chardonnay or white Burgundy.</li>

  <li><strong>Sauce Components Drive Final Wine Choice</strong> - Hollandaise or butter-based sauces call for rich, oaked Chardonnays or white Rhône blends, while citrus-herb preparations shine with Sauvignon Blanc's herbaceous notes. Teriyaki or soy-based glazes require wines with residual sugar like off-dry Riesling to balance the saltiness and umami.</li>

  <li><strong>Decanting Decisions for Red Wine Pairings</strong> - Young Pinot Noirs (under 5 years) benefit from 30 minutes of decanting to soften tannins that might clash with salmon's delicate proteins, while mature Burgundies should be decanted just before serving to preserve their ethereal aromatics that complement the fish's subtle flavors.</li>

  <li><strong>Glassware Impacts Salmon Wine Pairings</strong> - Use Burgundy glasses for both red and white wines with salmon—the wider bowl concentrates delicate aromas that might be lost in standard wine glasses, while the shape directs wine to the front palate where salmon's sweetness is best perceived. Avoid large Bordeaux glasses that can make medium-bodied wines taste thin.</li>

  <li><strong>Optimal Drinking Windows for Salmon Wines</strong> - Most salmon-friendly wines are best consumed within 3-5 years of vintage when their fruit-forward character complements the fish's natural sweetness. Exception: Premier Cru Chablis develops mineral complexity after 7-10 years that creates stunning partnerships with simply prepared salmon.</li>

  <li><strong>Regional Pairing Logic Works</strong> - Pacific Northwest Pinot Gris naturally complements regional salmon due to shared terroir influences—both develop in cool, maritime climates that create balanced acidity and clean flavors. Similarly, Loire Valley wines like Muscadet pair beautifully with Atlantic salmon, as centuries of coastal cuisine evolution has proven these combinations work harmoniously.</li>
</ol>

