<div class="space-y-6">
  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">What's the difference between wines for grilled salmon versus poached salmon?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Grilled salmon develops a smoky, caramelized crust that pairs beautifully with medium-bodied reds like Pinot Noir or robust whites like oaked Chardonnay. Poached salmon retains its delicate texture and subtle flavors, making it ideal for lighter wines such as Albariño, Sancerre, or unoaked Burgundian whites that won't overpower the fish's natural taste.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">Should I serve white or red wine with salmon?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Both work excellently with salmon due to its meaty texture and rich oils. White wines like Chardonnay, Riesling, and Sauvignon Blanc complement salmon's delicate flavors, while light to medium-bodied reds such as Pinot Noir, Beaujolais, and Sangiovese enhance its robust character. The cooking method and sauce typically determine the best choice.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">What wine pairs best with salmon teriyaki?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">The sweet-savory glaze of teriyaki salmon calls for wines with enough acidity to cut through the richness and complementary fruit notes. Off-dry Riesling, Gewürztraminer, or a fruit-forward Pinot Noir work exceptionally well. The slight sweetness in these wines harmonizes with the teriyaki while their acidity prevents the pairing from becoming cloying.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">Is salmon and wine pairing good for wine beginners?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Absolutely! Salmon is one of the most forgiving fish for wine pairing due to its rich, meaty texture that works with both whites and light reds. Beginners can experiment with familiar varietals like Chardonnay or Pinot Noir without fear of clashing flavors. The fish's natural oils and mild flavor profile make it an excellent starting point for learning food and wine pairing principles.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">What's the biggest mistake when pairing wine with salmon?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">The most common error is choosing wines that are too heavy or tannic, which overpower salmon's delicate flavors. Full-bodied Cabernet Sauvignon or heavily oaked whites can mask the fish's subtle taste. Another mistake is ignoring the preparation method—a wine perfect for cedar plank salmon might clash with salmon in cream sauce.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">What budget-friendly wines work well with salmon?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Excellent affordable options include Portuguese Vinho Verde, Spanish Albariño, Oregon Pinot Gris, and Washington State Riesling, typically ranging from $12-18. For reds, Loire Valley Sancerre Rouge, Beaujolais-Villages, or domestic Pinot Noir from Monterey County offer great value. These wines provide the acidity and flavor profiles that complement salmon without breaking the bank.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">Can sparkling wine be served with salmon?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Sparkling wines are excellent with salmon, especially smoked or cured preparations. Champagne, Cava, or Prosecco's effervescence and acidity cut through the fish's rich oils while cleansing the palate. Blanc de Blancs Champagne pairs particularly well with simply prepared salmon, while rosé sparklers complement salmon with herbs or light fruit salsas.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">What temperature should I serve wine with salmon?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Serve white wines at 45-50°F to maintain their crisp acidity and prevent them from becoming too warm alongside hot salmon. Light reds like Pinot Noir should be served slightly chilled at 55-60°F, which enhances their fruit character and prevents the tannins from overwhelming the fish. This temperature difference also creates a pleasant contrast with the warm salmon dish.</p>
  </div>
